Step 2: Connect Both PCs

Since only 2 computers, use Copper Cross-Over Cable

Steps:
Click Connections (lightning icon)
Select Copper Cross-Over Cable
Click PC0
Select FastEthernet0
Click PC1
Select FastEthernet0

Now both PCs are connected.

Step 3: Configure IP Address (PC0)
Click PC0
Go to Desktop
Click IP Configuration

Enter:

Field	Value
IP Address	192.168.1.1
Subnet Mask	255.255.255.0
Default Gateway	(Leave blank)

Close window

Step 4: Configure IP Address (PC1)
Click PC1
Go to Desktop
Click IP Configuration

Enter:

Field	Value
IP Address	192.168.1.2
Subnet Mask	255.255.255.0
Default Gateway	(Leave blank)

Close window

Step 5: Test Connectivity using Ping

Now check if both computers communicate.

From PC0
Click PC0
Desktop → Command Prompt
Type:
ping 192.168.1.2

Press Enter

Expected Output
Reply from 192.168.1.2
Reply from 192.168.1.2
Reply from 192.168.1.2
Reply from 192.168.1.2

This means Connection Successful ✅

Step 6: Test Ping from PC1
Click PC1
Desktop → Command Prompt
Type:
ping 192.168.1.1

If replies come → Network working
Step 7: Resource Sharing (File Sharing)

Now we simulate resource sharing

Create File in PC0
Click PC0
Desktop → Text Editor
Write:
Hello from PC0
Save as:
file.txt
Access File from PC1
Click PC1
Desktop → Command Prompt
Type:
ftp 192.168.1.1

OR

Use Web Browser if HTTP server configured

(For basic labs, ping testing is usually enough)
